		{
			"id": 1,
			"parent": 2,
			"text": "To fully understand a sequence of utterances , ",
			"relation": "enablement"
		},
		{
			"id": 2,
			"parent": 5,
			"text": "one must be able to infer implicit relationships between the utterances . <S>",
			"relation": "bg-goal"
		},
		{
			"id": 3,
			"parent": 4,
			"text": "Although the identification of sets of utterance relationships forms the basis for many theories of discourse , ",
			"relation": "contrast"
		},
		{
			"id": 4,
			"parent": 5,
			"text": "the formalization and recognition of such relationships has proven to be an extremely difficult computational task . <S>",
			"relation": "bg-goal"
		},
		{
			"id": 5,
			"parent": 0,
			"text": "This paper presents a plan-based approach to the representation and recognition of implicit relationships between utterances . <S>",
			"relation": "ROOT"
		},
		{
			"id": 6,
			"parent": 5,
			"text": "Relationships are formulated as discourse plans , ",
			"relation": "elab-aspect"
		},
		{
			"id": 7,
			"parent": 6,
			"text": "which allows their representation in terms of planning operators and their computation via a plan recognition process . <S>",
			"relation": "elab-addition"
		},
		{
			"id": 8,
			"parent": 9,
			"text": "By incorporating complex inferential processes ",
			"relation": "manner-means"
		},
		{
